{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_fanny_ver01/data/sn85040310/00514152305/1921032401/0616.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nThe Telegraph- Courier\nPUBLISHED WEEKLY AT KENOSHA, WIS,\nW- T. Marlatt Editor and Publisher\nThe Oldest Newspaper of Continuous\nPublication in Wisconsin\nSUBSCRIPTION ONE DOLLAR A YEAR IN ADVANCE\nEntered as Second Class Matter at the Post Office at\nKenosha, Under Act of Mar<fh 3, 1873.\nVOLUME LXXXI, NO. 49.\nTHURSDAY, MARCH 24,1921\nPHILIPPINES AS COMMERCIAL BASE\n\u201cThe desire of President Harding to have a\nfirst-hand report on the Philippine situation is\ntaken in quarters where such an eventuality is\nhoped for as an augury of granting of independ\nence,\u201d says the Christian Science Monitor, in\ncommenting on the assignment of General\nWood to the Philippine Islands on k general mis\nsion. Just who is hoping for such an event\nuality, outside of a few Filipina malcontents\nwho would like to introduce an Orientalized\nTweed system in those islands, is not stated.\nCertainly as the educated Filipinos witness the\navidness of Japan in sweeping the Pacific is\nlands into her basket their thoughts must be\nturned to the safety which American control of\ntheir territory assures. The Filipinos are not\nso far from Korea but what they appreciate\nwhat Japanese imperialism would mean to\nthem.\nThe. Democratic Administration included in\nthe many promises which it made in 1912 a\npromise of independence to the Philippines.\nThat party was in power for eight years and\nthis promise went by the board as did\nothers. In fact, if there is any virtue in\nbreaking a promise the Democrats should be\ncredited with it in this instance.\nIn the first place, the Filipinos are not pre\npared for self-determination in the fullest\nsense of the word. They have as much of it\nas they can handle right now. They have their\nown legislature, their own courts, and their\nown officials. Outside of a Governor and a\nLieutenant-Governor the Philipinos occupy\npractically every office in their administration.\nOurs is a guiding hand, not a mailed fist in our\ncolonies.\nIn the second place, the situation is such in\nthe Far East at the present moment, and prob\nably will be so for some years to come, as to\nmake it imparative that we retain a foothold\nin that quarter of the globe. The secret treaty\nbetween England and Japan by which tfie\nformer acquired all of the German insular ter\nritories in the Pacific south, and the latter all\nthose north of the equator, now threatens us\nwith the loss of even our cable station at Yap\nIsland; while the purpose of Japan to attempt\nto close the door which John Hay opened, and\nher all but acknowledged policy of securing\nthe control of the Pacific, indicate how import\nant it is that we have a listening-post in the\nOrient.\nForesighted Filipinos will not overlook the\nfact that if Japan should succeed in turning\nthe Pacific Ocean into a vast Nipponese lake\nthe insular territory stretching from Batan to\nthe Tawi Tawi group would come under a des\npotism more efficient than that of Hapsburg or\nHohenzollem.\nDRESS AND THE WOMAN\nDress makes or breaks a woman, so far as\nappearances are concerned.\nIf you doubt this, just take a look in the old\nfamily album.\nWhat a commentary it is on the varying de\ngrees of ugliness that women affect from time\nto time according to the mandates of style.\nForms that might have served as models for\nGreek goddesses are pinched into corsets that\nleave no hint of the grace and beauty conceal\ned within that instrument of torture.\nBrows that might have graced a Madonna are\nhidden behind mops of bangs or frizzes that\ndisfigure rather than enhance their natural\nbeauty.\nIn fact, it is exceptional to find a single wo\nman to whom the dress is so admirably adapted\nthat it has survived the lapse of time and still\nreveals lines of beauty.\nBut women are learning, and it may be that\nthe lesson of the old family album has had no\nlittle share in bringing about the reforms that\nare so apparent in woman\u2019s dress.\nWomen are learning the art of adapting the\ndress to the individual rather than the indiv\nidual to the dress, with the result that they are\nbetter dressed than ever before.\nI hey are learning that simplicity and fitness\nare the two ideals to be sought in dress, rather\nthan slavish conformity to any particular\nmode.\nIS YOURS A \u201cDUSTY\u201d BIBLE?\nIn a recent motion picture occurs a trivial\nincident, the significance of which is quickly\ngrasped by everyone in the audience.\nThe villain of the play reaches into his book\nease for a Bible. Before opening it, he blows\ndust from its edges. A mere gesture, but\nit is one of the best touches in the play. The\naudience understands and smiles appreciation.\nThe incident holds the mirror up to a familiar\nthing in many homes\u2014a dusty Bible.\nLying unused on many shelves it offers in\nvain its wisdom, its consolation and its romance\nwhile the unsated hearts of the owners seek in\nvain for new thrills in the best sellers.\nWho knows a sweeter story than the book\nof Ruth? And tragedy more sublime than the\nstory of the Crucifixion And philosophy more\nwholesome than that of Ecclesiastes, or of the\nProverbs? Or poetry finer than the Song of\nSolomon\nThe Bible has the wonderful quality of being\nalways new, presenting unexplored depths of\nlight at every reading. It is like one of those\nwonderful old attics of our childhood days\nwhere at every visit, we would discover, hidden\naway, something we had missed on our last\nvisit.\n\u201cAn active mind,\u201d said President John Quin\ncy Adams, \u201ccannot peruse a single chapter and\nlay the book aside to think, and take it up\nagain tomorrow, without finding in it advice\nfor our own conduct, which we may turn to use\nful account in the progress of our daily pilgrim\nage on earth.\u201d\nAt a recent meeting of the National Press\nclub ill Washington, when President Harding\nand V ice President Coolidge were guests of\nhonor, Secretary of Commerce Hoover was in\ntroduced as a newspaper man, being part own\ner of the Washington Herald. It is to be hoped\nthat the Herald and the Marion Star will not\nget on opposite sides of important national\nissues.\nOf course the st\u00a3te legislature fails to look\nupon the local communities as worthy of great\nconsideration when it comes to tax laws. The\nstate needs money and it wants to take the\neasiest way to get it. The better way is to\nreduce the demands of the state by strict econ\nomy and let the local communities have what\nis coming to them from the tax bills.\nThe Washington Herald, one of whose own\ners is Secretary of Commerce Herbert Hoover,\nis strenuously seconding the vigorous advice of\nSecretary of the Treasury Mellon that the Gov\nernment avoid an\u00a3 new undertakings that will\ncall foi increased expenditures. The more sup\nport this policy gets, the better.\nIt may be a little early to start the garden\nout in the back yard but it won\u2019t hurt a bit to\nget the yard cleaned up and get for the\ngarden now. It\u2019s the earty bird who wins when\nit comes to gardening just like anything else.\nNational Live Stock Association wants rates\ni educed so it can ship freight, so the railroads\ncan haul cars, so they can give employment to\ntheir workers, and so they can stop growling\nabout the business depression.\nChief of Police at Sunbury, Pa., rules women\nmust weai skirts four inches below knees.\nClass legislation in favor of the lopger-ljmbed\neh?\nSure prohibition is coming. Listen to this.\nThe Milwaukee is going to be chris\ntened with a bottle of Lake Michigan water.\nThe meanest thief probably lives in Lingle,\nWyo., for there it was that somebody stole a\nbaby s bottle while mother was shopping.\n\u201cCousin Andy\u201d Mellon, new secretary of the\ntreasury, has acquired a new nickname: \u201cThe\nman of the tired eye.\u201d\n\u201cThe day of the vampire is waning,\u201d observe\nTheaa Bara. A few gray hairs and some\nwrinkles do it, eh?\nThat excass profits tax is going to be as\npopular in the 67th Congress as a crutch is in\na foot race.\ni\nThere are some who believe business needs\nmore pep, but everybody is agreed that it needs\nmore dollars.\nAnd those who sell gold bricks to farmers\nare loud in their complaint against low farm\nprices.\nNo man finds consolation in that a cut in his\nwages means a cut in his next year\u2019s income\ntax.\nOne way to increase the number of law viola\ntors is to increase the number of laws.\nIncluded in the wages of sin are the defend\ning lawyer\u2019s fees.\nEvery baseball manager today is counting\nunhatched chickens.\nUsually the man who spades for a garden\nisn\u2019t the man who spades for angleworms.\nGermany now is learning in a different\n\u201cschool of might.\u201d\nThe allies are more intent upon collecting the\ncoin than in convicting the kaiser.\nTHE TELEGRAPH-COURIER\n\u25a0/'Q.-KTdii I!\n1\nNk x 7 C J \"1\nV WHA-t'S THt\nI< Ww X\ni 1X \u2014X w\nHomely Hank's\nQuestion Box\nIn la.y Saturday\u2019s issue of the News,\nHomely-Hank asked how old an alli\ngator must be before it turned into a\ntraveling bag. Mrs. James Leech of\n581 Newell street has an original an\nswer that she gave over the phone.\n\"The alligator must be baggage, (bagg\nage) of course. It's simple isn\u2019t it?\u201d\nasked Mrs. Leech, and hung up.\nSports.\n1\u2014 \u2014Does a cricket enthusiast become\na bug?\n2ln fly fishing, is tanglefoot con\nsidered a good bait?\n3 How may one retain his good na\nture during a cross-country run\n4ln a gruelling contest, who is ex\npected to pay for the gruel?\nsln stalking a gazelle, is it good\nform to use the handkerchief flirta\ntion\nYesterday\u2019s Questions Answered.\n1\u2014 At athletic meets, it is best to\nleave one\u2019s valuables in the pole vault.\n2 \u2018\u2018Keep Off the Grass\u201d signs are\ngradually doing away with fencing in\nthis\u2019country.\n3 LaCrosse is considered good sport\nby the folks who live in Fond du Lac\nand \\Appleton.\n4 The man with the iron mask was\nnot a baseball catcher.\n5 The prize ring should be worn on\nthe third finger of the right hand.\nDid U ever git cot out inn a rane?\nHuh? Lass Sunday we wuz out wawk\nen wuz bout 3 miles or sew out inn\nthe kuntry- itt smarted 2 luk like itt\nwuz goen 2 rane we inkreased our\nSpede then thee furst few drops\nkum we started 2 trot then itt\nstarted 2 rane inn urnust. Gee, Hank,\nbutt wuz wee wet?\nSum feller kum along inna sedan\nwee flags him hee sorta slows up\nlike hee wuz goen 2 stop then hee\nsteps oun thee gas there we wuz.\nPurty sune sum feller inn a big car\nwith 3 gurls picks us up brings us\n2 thee fare sity uv Keno. Then did.\nU evur juss enjoy gitten in 2 cloze\nthat dident fit, setten doun eaten a\ngood hot supper? Huh, Hank thems\nthee best things inn thee Heres\nhopen that thee wether man don\u2019t fur\ngit 2 send sum moar ranes\u2014\n(Suggestion: Yores fur thee wets,),\nJIM.\nSum fellers R sew urnust bout he-en\nurnust* that they taik the joy outa\nlife. Grin, its good fur U thee\nwurld. Thee wurld luves a cheerful\ngrinner.\nSOMEONE SAVES MONEY.\nWichita, Kas, \u201427 years ago Col. D.\nR. Green, then treasurer of Grant\ncounty, Okla., received the first money\npaid in for taxes, in that county in the\nform of a $5 bill. He noted the fact,\nand the date on the back of the bill\nin red ink. A few days ago the bill\nappeared at a bank here. It has been\nsent to Green, now in California.\nNEW SOURCE OF SALT.\nCalgary, Can. \u2014The saltiest body of\nwater in the world is the Dead Sea,\nat Senlac, say Calgary capitalists who\nare exploiting it. Salt content of the\nSenlac lake is five times greater than\nthat of Great Salt Lake in Utah. Sci\nentists say it will furnish enough salt\nfor all western Canada, hitherto de\npendent on Utah.\nREAL SNAKE BITES TOO.\nBombay, India. \u2014Nearly 21,000 Hin\ndus were killed by snake bites last\nyear, the government announces. Man\neating tigers during the year killed\n1,162 Hindus, leoprads killed 469, wild\nbears 201, wolves 294, crocodiles 185,\nelephants 60 and hyenas 33.\nTHIS JUDGE KEEPS BUSY.\nHuangyuen, China. \u2014This town boasts\nthe most active judge in the world.\nHe\u2019s magistrate Ki Lo, presiding over\nall court business in Huangyuen. In\nspare time he\u2019s building three school\nhouses and a Uenmiad, or Confucius\ntemple.\nAbout This Time o\u2019 Year\nDoins\u2019 of Troop E\nBy K. P.\nThe last that we saw of Bugler\nTaylor was out behind the stable prac\nticing pay call. Taylor says that it\nis so long since he got paid that he\ndoesn\u2019t remember how pay call goes.\nZ\nThe gang won\u2019t need any bugle to\ntejl them that \u201cjack\u201d 'has come in.\nGottlieb knows it and Gottlieb is a\ngood advertiser.\nBilly Weiss says that there is a fly\nin the ointment about pay day. Bijly\nadmits that it is nice to get some gov\nernment money but says that gang\nwill now expect him to furnish his\nown cigarettes. How about another\nparty for Billy, Captain?\nEven Dynamite seems to know that\nsomething unusual is coming off, We\nrefer to the rumor that the tropp is\ngoing to get paid.\nFrom the trouble that a certain\nsecond lieutenant of Troop E, and we\naren\u2019t mentioning any names, but he\nrides a fourth of July horse, had with\na motorcycle recently, our advice to\nhim be stick to Red. Now we\nsuppose that the particular second\nlieutenant that we have in mind will\nalibi by saying that he had trouble\nbecause it wasn\u2019t an Indian motorcycle\nand wasn\u2019t painted red.\nOne trooper remarked that the cap\ntain was a good scout and would give\na fellow his lasl pair of trousers.\n\u201cYeh, but see where he orders you to\nif you ask him for his old hat,\u201d re\nplied the second trooper.\nHow about a baseball team, troopers?\nNow\u2019s the time to get one started.\nLet\u2019s get in the city league with the\nDairymen, the Banks, the Rode Studio\nand show them that we are on the\nmap. Huh? How about it?\nThe troop would appreciate any sort\nof athletic equipment that the folks\nof the city would care to donate. The\ntroop is trying to equip a gymnasium\nand needs dumb bells, boxing gloves,\nfencing foils, medicine balls, and all\nsort of athletic gear. Just call 53 on\nthe phone and there will be a trooper\ncall at your home.\nIt sure does pay to advertise! Since\ngetting \u201cDere Hank\u201d Rush, the sea\ngoing cavalry man in the troop an\nother ex-gob has signed up. His name\nis Edwan Johann and was out riding\nSunday morning. Any more ex-navy\nmen of the city that would like to\n\u201chitch up\u201d with Troop E? Talk it\nover with any of the troopers. Every\none of them is a recruiting officer.\nEven Sullivan is all set for the in\nspection. Attention, Sullivan!\nThe people of the city are invited\nto come down and look over the Troop\nE stables at any time. Have you ever\nseen trained cavalry horses? Few\npeople realize that Kenosha has a cav\nalry troop, .in Federal service but an\ninspection of the troop stables would\nsoon convince anyone that tjje troop is\na live organization.\nThe writer of the little verse at the\ntop of the column apologizes for it.\nDon\u2019t kill him before inspection, how\never, as the captain is counting on\nevery man to be at said inspection\ntonight. After inspection, use your\ndiscretion. It doesn\u2019t matter.\nLieutenant Charles Melone, one time\nsergeant of old Troop E of war days\nhas felt the call and was a visitor at\nthe stables last Sunday morning and\nwe may expect to see the former Loot\nwith us next Sunday morning for our\nregular little joy ride.'\nSullivan, it is reported, is up for his\ncorporal\u2019s rating. He can stand at\nattention new and yesterday we saw\nhim going through mounted drill.\nDespite frantic applications of hair\nHappenings\n25 Years Ago\nFifteen men had been sentenced to\nWaupun during the years 1894, 1895\nai)d 1896 from Kenosha county. At\ntorney Buckmaster was at that time\nprosecuting attorney.\nKenosha has just purchased a new\nfire engine of the latest improved type.\nThere was an attempt twenty-five\nyears ago to revive the county fair.\nHistory repeats itself evidently, judg\ning from the recent talk of reviving\nthe fair again by the manufacturers,\nretailers and farmers of the city.\nRetirement of Law\nWeakens Cabinet\n(By Associated Press!\nLondon.\u2014-A political crisis of th#\nfirst magnitude has been created by\nthe retirement of A. Bonar Law from\nthe British cabinet, it is declared by\nthe London Times. Other newspapers,\nwhile less emphatic, agree in saying\nthat Bonar Laxy\u2019s resignation is cer\ntain to have considerable political ef\nfect and that it probably will material\nly weaken the coalition yovernment.\nIt is pointed out that no successor to\nBonar Law is likely to work so well\nwith Prime Minister Lloyd George and\nthe Graphic even suggests that if Mr.\nLloyd George is called upon to face a\nprospect of unsympathetic association,\nhe may find the strain of office intol\nlerable and will follow Mr. Bonar Law\ninto retirement.\nTwo Gun Bandit\nShot to Death\n(By Associated Press',\nChicago.\u2014Facing more than 50 po\nlicemen, a two-gun bandit today was\nshot to death after he had kept up a\nsteady fight with them until his am\nmunition was exhausted. Several po\nlicemen were wounded and one, Detec\ntive Mix, is in a critical condition.\nMix, noticing the bandit loafing around\na street corner early today, started to\nquestion him. The man opened fire\nand ran. Reinforcements came and\nthe bandit finally was cornered.\ntonic, cologne, beauty preparations and\nother hair producers, \u201cYoung Aleck\u201d\nis unable to show any shadow on his\nlip. We hope that pink isn\u2019t his fa\nvorite color. Sergeant Rhode please\ncopy.\nE TROOP PAY CALL.\nWhile drillin\u2019 ain\u2019t no joke,\nYet a trooper\u2019s always broke,\nUntil \u2014another pay eall.\nLay aside your little jokes,\nListen to those bugle notes,\nHey, troopers, it\u2019s pay call!\nListen to old Taylor tooten,\nSoon the bones we\u2019ll all be shooten,\nAfter pay call.\nGee, ain\u2019t that a welcome sound,\nWhen we\u2019ve waited the whole year\nround\nFor pay call?\nThen we\u2019ll all take in a show,\nTo a feed, ourselves we\u2019ll blow,\nAfter pay call!\nBilly then will have cigarettes,\nNo more bumming from suffrag\nettes\nFor him, after pay call.\nThen every trooper\u2019ll get a chance\nTo buy a ticket for the dance!\nEh, Captain, after pay call?\nBut we\u2019ll bet you a dollar bill,\nThat they\u2019ll all be out to drill,\nAfter pay call.\nFor they\u2019re loyal to E Troop,\nAfter all is said and done,\nAfter all is shot and won,\nOr lost after pay call,\nDon\u2019t you think it would be niee,\nIf the troopers got the price\nTo give a party? After pay eall?\n-\u201cHank\u201d.\nFRIEND OF GIRLS\nCALLED BY DEATH\nMrs. Ellen Mac Neil, Stalker\nDied on Thursday After\nLong Illness.\nWAS BADGER PIONEER\nWife of Dr. H. J. Stalker Was\nInterested in Societies\nfor Young Women.\n\nMrs. Ellen Mac Neill Stalker, wife of\nDr, H. J. Stalker, aged 85 years, one\nof the most estimable local women\nand one of the pioneer women of Wis\nconsin died at the home of her daugh\nter, Mrs. Albert E. Buckmaster, 463\nExchange street just after ten o\u2019clock\nThursday evening following an ill\nness from a complication o f\ndiseases, Mrs. Stalker had been\nin failing health for many months and\nfor the past three weeks she had been\nconfined to her room with an acute\nattack of intestinal trouble. Surgeons\nhad operated on her on Thltrsday\nmorning in hopes of prolonging her life\nand the operation came as a relief\nto her in the last hours of suffering.\nMrs. Stalker was widely known in Ke\nnosha on account of her great interest\nin many movements for bettering the\ncondition of young women and for\ncjvjc uplift and the announcement of\nher death comes as a personal sorrow\nin many homes.\nWas a Native of Vermont.\nMrs. Stalker was a native of Ver\nmont. She was a daughter of the late\nJoseph Mac Neill one of the pioneer\nsettlers of Wisconsin and she was\nborn at Andover, Vt., August 15, 1835,\nShe came to Wisconsin with her par\nents when she was three yaars old\nand the family settled at Waukesha.\nShe was educated in the schools at\nWaukesha and Appleton and at Apple\nton on March 1, 1866, she was married\nto Dr. H. J, Stalker. After their mar\nriage Dr. and Mrs. Stalker lived for a\nshort time at Lime Springs, lowa, but\nthey returned to Wisconsin and settled\nat Mauston where Dr. Stalker was for\nmany years a leading practicing phys\nician and where his wife was a leader\nin social an 1 church work, Dr. and\nMrs, Stalker came to Kenosha to make\ntheir home in 1902 and they had since\nbeen residents of Keposha.\nTook Deep Interest in Girls.\nMrs. Stalker was a woman of edu\ncation and refinement with an intense\ninterest in every movement for the up\nlift of her fellow beings. She took an\nespecial interest in movements for\nthe advancement of the conditions\nsurrounding the young girls of Keno\nsha and she was a pioneer in all\nmovements for organizations to this\nend. She had strongly urged the or\nganization of a Y. W, C. A. for Keno\nsha and had given much of her time\nto interest other people in the Girls\u2019\nClub and other similar organizations.\nOnly a little while before she was\ntaken with the acute illness which\ncaused her death she had sought to\norganise support for a new movement\nwhich would bring better conditions\nfor the girls of Kenosha.\nMrs. Stalker was one of the oldest\nand most active members of the Keno\nsha branch of the Woman\u2019s Christian\nTemperance Union and she had re\ntained her interest in the work of this\norganization until a few weeks ago.\nMember of Revolutionary Family.\nMrs. Stalker traced her lineage to\none of the most prominent of the rev\nolutionary families and, she was a\nmember of the Kenosha Chapter of the\nDaughters of the American Revolution.\nA devout Christian woman she was\nan active member of the First Baptist\nOutbursts of Everett True\nI r Wz\nz _ A\nANjD I'lu HELP\nYOU f=< TH6 CS-UTTSR YHAT I\nYcaj THWUf THE MIODLCS OF Tn\u2019S i\nTBSSSfawK\nTOPETE!\nTHURSDAY, MARCH 24, 1921\nCLARA SMITH PLANS\nTO ANEW\nWoman Acquitted of Murder of Mil\nlionaire Will Face World De\ntermined to Win.\ni (Copyright 1921 by the United Pres\nI Clara Smith Hamon, who was acquit\nted yesterday of the charge of kill\ning Jake L Hamon, wrote the foi\nlowing message for the United Press\n(By Clara Smith Hamon)\nArdmore. Okla. I start anew h\nI life with the scarlet letter of sham\ni branded on my breast. But I star\n'opt with the determination to shot\nthe world that an erring woman ea\nI come back.\nIt has been said that the world nev\ner forgives a woman who makes on\nmistake in life; that society will neve\nitake her back in the fold.\nIf I believed that the liberty given t\nme by the jury yesterday would nc\n\u25a0be sweet to me, it would be as bit\nI ter as hemlock. I know the world wi.\nbe sympathetic with the belief that\n\u25a0am a regenerated woman. I am goin\nthrough life with my head up, knowin\nnow that I can look every man an\nevery woman in the eye unashame\nWith this spirit I know I can win;\nhave willed to win.\nI want to thank the people of th\nnation for being sympathetic with n>\nin my time of need. I appreciate tl\nhundreds of messages I received fro\npersons all over the country durin\nthe ordeal.\nWhat am I going to do now that\njam free? I wish I knew. Before\ndecide I want my mind to becon\nj clearer the sordid happenings\ni last week, are still wheeling before m\nI plan to leave soon for California wi'\nmy brother and pal, Jimmie. Thei\nunder new skies and different sis\nroundings I will map out my futur\nBut I am coming back to Ardmore ar\nthe southwest I want to win rig,\nhere among the people I know ai\nlove.\nLabor Presents\nBill of Right\n(By Associated Press)\nChicago The railroad labor unior\ntoday presented what they terme\ntheir \u201cBill of Rights\u201d to the railroa\nlabor board and then began an attac\nupon the insincerity of the roads i\ndealing with the unions.\nBuyers Strike\nCost a Billioi\n(By United Press)\nWashington The buyers strike, th\nnation business depression an\nthe reduced earnings of workers an\nprofessional men in 1920 will cost th\ngovernjment approximately $1,000,000.\n000 in reduced tax payments this yea\nit was indicated here today in an earb\nreport of the inspector of incomes an\nexcess profits tax of March 15.\nTO* SWEAR LN COMPANY K.\n(By United Press!\nMilwaukee The newly\nCompany K of the Wisconsin Nationa\nGuard, will be sworn in here tonighi\nThe company, known as the \u201cKosciu\nsko guard\u201d is composed entirely o\nmen of Polish descent, more than hal\nof whom overseas in the wort\nwar.\nChurch and she gave much time to th,\nwork of the church. An infinite sorrov\nis felt for the surviving husbano\nThrough a life of more than fifty-fiv<\nyears they had enjoyed a delightfu\ncomradeship. Mrs. Stalker is also\nsurvived by one daughter, Mrs. Buck\nmaster.\nThe remains will be taken to th*\nold home at Mauston for intermen:\nthe burial to take place on Sunday as\nternoon. A short funeral service wa\nheld at the late residence on Sat\nurday afternoon at three o\u2019clock.\nBy Condo","height":"25512","width":"20607"}}
